{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01TQ3Q7g2Jkf8t66UqGvTHvf","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Python 3.10.12 is available on the blue pod. I can write a Python script to:\n1. Get all messages from blue (without consuming - using ack_requeue_true)\n2. Publish them to green\n\nLet me write a Python script that:\n1. Connects to the blue management API to get all messages (peek with requeue)\n2. Connects to the green management API to publish them\n\nFor peeking without consuming, I'll use:\n- `POST /api/queues/%2Fapp/app-queue/get` with `ackmode: \"ack_requeue_true\"`\n- `POST /api/exchanges/%2Fapp/amq.default/publish` with the message payload to green\n\nThe blue pod can reach the green cluster via `rabbitmq-green.karma-rabbitmq-blue-green-migration-2-0095c963-target.svc.cluster.local:15672`. But I'm realizing the management API's GET endpoint is really a basic.get AMQP operation, and with ack_requeue_true it returns messages one at a time without a way to fetch all of them at once.\n\nLooking at the RabbitMQ management HTTP API more carefully: the `/get` endpoint with `ack_requeue_true` peeks at messages by requeuing them at the tail, which could mess up ordering if I call it repeatedly. But I can request up to 50 messages in a single call with count=50, so I'll fetch all messages at once and then publish them to green without worrying about reordering issues.\n\nFor the migration, I'll use `ack_requeue_true` to capture the payloads of all 50 messages, publish them to green, and then either leave the blue queue as-is or flush it afterward depending on what the task requires.\n\nNow I'm writing the Python script to handle this.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1611,"cache_read_input_tokens":42069,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1611},"output_tokens